Phase 3.1 Verified Behavior (Timezone & Day Shift)
Status: Verified and locked after Phase 3.1 testing.
The scheduling system must preserve the following behavior:

1. Anchor Time Stability
- The anchor timezone (e.g. America/New_York) is the source of truth for meeting date and time.
- Anchor date and time must remain stable across all generated weeks.
- DST transitions must not cause anchor local time to drift.

Example:
- NY 09:00 must always remain 09:00 in NY,
- even when UTC offset changes (UTC-05 → UTC-04).
2. Correct Local Day Conversion
For every participant:
- UTC → IANA timezone → local time → local date
- If the local time crosses midnight relative to the anchor date:
- Next day must be labeled (+1 day)
- Previous day must be labeled (-1 day)

Example:
- NY: Fri Apr 10 02:30
- Sophia: Thu Apr 9 23:30  (-1 day)
- NY: Fri Apr 17 16:30
- Kenji: Sat Apr 18 05:30  (+1 day)
3. UI and Computation Must Match
- For any member and week:
- The displayed day shift must match the actual timezone conversion.
- UI labels must never contradict the computed local time.

4. Change Control
- Any future changes to:
- timezone conversion
- rotation scheduling
- date calculation
- display timezone
must NOT break Phase 3.1 verified behavior.
Regression of:
- anchor time drift
- incorrect +1/-1 day labeling
- UI/date mismatch is not allowed.

5. Testing Priority
- During current development:
- Algorithm correctness > UI polish
- UI, styling, and design may change later, but timezone and scheduling correctness must remain stable.

Phase 3.2 (Week Iteration Stability)
- The scheduling engine must preserve weekday alignment and +7-day iteration across rotation weeks.

Rules verified in Phase 3.2:
- Each generated week must remain on the configured day_of_week.
- Week dates must increment strictly by +7 days from the anchor start date.
- Month rollover and year rollover must be handled correctly (e.g., Dec → Jan).
- Anchor timezone (displayTimezone) is the source of truth for weekday validation.

Constraints:
- Do not modify week iteration logic (utcStart.plus({ weeks: i })) unless a regression is proven.
- Any future change affecting week generation must preserve:
- weekday stability
- correct month/year rollover
- deterministic +7 day progression.
